        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-01T21:42:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "How much is this actually buying us? Normally we try to minimize the dependencies required by Minijail -- is this easier than just splitting the audit line by spaces and then parsing key\u003dvalue pairs?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 32,
        "startChar": 11,
        "endLine": 32,
        "endChar": 18
      },
      "revId": "e45f51da9bc158940c08e0fb2905893327a34d4a",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bf14d1bc_1ed21917",
        "filename": "tools/generate_seccomp_policy.py",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 32,
      "author": {
        "id": 1806960
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-02T02:11:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I did briefly consider dropping this also because of how clunky the API is. Parsing is one aspect. I agree that for our purposes, a simple regex or split will do the job. The other, bigger advantage of using auparse is interpret_field(). auparse has lookup tables to convert syscall numbers and integer arguments from audit logs into human readable names. That gives us easy parity with strace parsing. IMO this is worth the dependency.\nList of builtin lookup tables for reference: https://git.io/JITmR\n\nI know this doesn\u0027t allay your philosophical concern fully but auparse seems to be available by default in the Chrome OS chroot at least.",
      "parentUuid": "d4d4f5f0_d6dbaa8a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 32,
        "startChar": 11,
        "endLine": 32,
        "endChar": 18
      },
      "revId": "e45f51da9bc158940c08e0fb2905893327a34d4a",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bb06fcf2_d3205bff",
        "filename": "tools/generate_seccomp_policy.py",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 32,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-02T14:54:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t see that auparse is buying us much, if anything. You need to define a helper function because of its weirdness parsing records (_find_field_in_current_record). The definition of stuff to search for is pretty much identical to what you would do for text search:\n\n\"\"\"\nau.search_add_item(\u0027type\u0027, \u0027\u003d\u0027, \u0027SECCOMP\u0027, auparse.AUSEARCH_RULE_CLEAR)\n    au.search_add_item(\u0027type\u0027, \u0027\u003d\u0027, \u0027SYSCALL\u0027, auparse.AUSEARCH_RULE_OR)\n    au.search_add_item(\u0027comm\u0027, \u0027\u003d\u0027, \u0027\"%s\"\u0027 % audit_comm,\n\"\"\"\n\nAnd it adds the weirdness of keeping state with RULE_CLEAR and RULE_OR.\n\nAt this point my preference would be to not use this. Moreover, we already have a mapping of syscall numbers to syscall names (https://source.corp.google.com/chromeos_public/src/aosp/external/minijail/gen_syscalls.sh) which can be easily adapted to also spit out the mapping as a python file.\n\nEven more, our syscall code supports syscall numbers as well as syscall names so you can start by just printing syscall numbers into the policy and things will work, at least during development.",
      "parentUuid": "bf14d1bc_1ed21917",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 32,
        "startChar": 11,
        "endLine": 32,
        "endChar": 18
      },
      "revId": "e45f51da9bc158940c08e0fb2905893327a34d4a",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bda8cfcb_9b1fcc89",
        "filename": "tools/generate_seccomp_policy.py",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 32,
      "author": {
        "id": 1806960
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-02T18:08:52Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The RULE_CLEAR/RULE_OR for searching looks like a pretty standard declarative pattern. I do agree that the find_field is non-intuitive. It\u0027s because the python bindings are backed by a C library with a C API. So in that sense writing our helper wrappers on top of the C API doesn\u0027t seem out of the ordinary.\n\nWhat auparse buys us is that it already exists, it\u0027s part of the official audit API, and it works. Writing scripts to generate mappings (both syscall and args) per ELF arch, checking them into source control, and writing code for parsing and lookup is just (partially) reinventing the auparse wheel. Might as well use the official library instead of inventing our own. Philosophically, the auparse dependency is subsumed in the dependency on audit that we want to add here.\n\nWe can start with numbers but that will break the argument specific hacks that exist for mmap et al. Those will have to be handled separately.",
      "parentUuid": "bb06fcf2_d3205bff",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 32,
        "startChar": 11,
        "endLine": 32,
        "endChar": 18
      },
      "revId": "e45f51da9bc158940c08e0fb2905893327a34d4a",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3ed3a1e1_a18d3eb9",
        "filename": "tools/generate_seccomp_policy.py",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 83,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-01T21:42:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t think these should be mutually exclusive. You should be able to feed this script a bunch of files from strace and audit and it should spit out a valid policy.\n\nBonus points for removing the command line arguments and just detecting the files automatically.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 75,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 83,
        "endChar": 72
      },
      "revId": "e45f51da9bc158940c08e0fb2905893327a34d4a",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3c99847a_1a05943c",
        "filename": "tools/generate_seccomp_policy.py",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 83,
      "author": {
        "id": 1806960
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-02T02:11:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Done. I was on the fence about this before. The tool now correctly handles any number of strace and/or audit logs.\n\nOne way to auto detect file formats would be to let auparse have the first pass at parsing. If auparse fails, treat the file as a strace log. Though that adds a strong dependency on auparse. I can\u0027t think of any other great heuristics that would be worth the added convenience. The files don\u0027t have any headers, for example. Let me know what you think.",
      "parentUuid": "3ed3a1e1_a18d3eb9",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 75,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 83,
        "endChar": 72
      },
      "revId": "e45f51da9bc158940c08e0fb2905893327a34d4a",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0c33af19_0e201b8c",
        "filename": "tools/generate_seccomp_policy.py",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 83,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-02T14:54:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Per the above, I think we should get rid of auparse.\n\nThis script is a helper script. It doesn\u0027t need to be bulletproof and it doesn\u0027t need to solve the entire problem at once. If I were coding this I\u0027d search for type\u003dSECCOMP or type\u003dSYSCALL in the file, if it\u0027s found it\u0027s audit, otherwise it\u0027s strace.",
